content.text:
The issue was that `timeoutInternal` operator in `Delay.kt` ignored the exception when the upstream flow was closed with an exception. It simply returned `false` to the `whileSelect` loop, causing the flow to complete normally instead of propagating the exception.

I fixed this by checking for an exception in the `onClosed` block and throwing it if present. This ensures that if the upstream flow (like a `callbackFlow` closed with an exception) fails, the `timeout` operator also fails with the same exception.

I verified the fix with a reproduction test case that uses `callbackFlow` closed with an exception chained with `timeout`. The test failed before the fix and passed after the fix.

**Code Changes:**
Modified `kotlinx-coroutines-core/common/src/flow/operators/Delay.kt`:

```kotlin
            }.onClosed {
                it?.let { throw it }
                return@onReceiveCatching false
            }
```

This change was applied to the `timeoutInternal` function.

